• This is not a homework service. Please see How to Ask. – David Richerby Nov 4 '15 at 18:51

Freedom of speech is a complicated issue. The First Amendment to the United States Constitution states that Congress shall make no law abridging the freedom of speech, but this freedom is not absolute. There are a number of exceptions, and there are different standards for what is protected speech in different circumstances.

For example, the Supreme Court has ruled that hate speech is protected under the First Amendment, as long as it is not incitement to violence. In addition, the Court has held that false speech is protected, as long as it is not a defamation of character. Similarly, speech that is deemed obscene or offensive is also protected, as long as it is not libelous.

2. Keep your operating system and other software up to date: Software updates often include patches that address security vulnerabilities that could be exploited by viruses.

3. Avoid suspicious email attachments and links: Be cautious when opening email attachments and clicking on links, especially if they come from unknown senders or if they look suspicious.

4. Use strong passwords: Use strong, unique passwords for your email accounts, social media accounts, and other online accounts. Avoid using the same password for multiple accounts.

5. Use a firewall: A firewall can help protect your computer from unauthorized access and can prevent viruses from spreading to other computers on your network.

6. Regularly back up your data: Regularly backing up your data can help protect your files in case your computer becomes infected with a virus.

1. Disconnect from the internet: Disconnecting from the internet can prevent the virus from spreading to other computers and can also prevent it from updating or downloading new files.

2. Run a full system scan: Run a full system scan with your antivirus software to detect and remove any viruses that may be present.

3. Delete temporary files and cookies: Delete temporary files and cookies to remove any files that may have been downloaded by the virus.

4. Reboot in safe mode: Reboot your computer in safe mode to prevent the virus from loading and running. In safe mode, only essential system files and programs are loaded, which can help you remove the virus.

5. Use a malware removal tool: Use a malware removal tool to scan your computer for any viruses or other malicious software that may be present.

6. Restore your computer to a previous state: If all else fails, you may need to restore your computer to a previous state before the virus was present. This can be done using a backup or by using a system restore point.

In conclusion, computer viruses can be a serious threat to your computer and your data. How to poison a distracting notification on my laptop? ignore word: poisonassistant
predict:
When I work on my laptop I use a combination of a lot of programs, and sometimes I have a notification from one of them that distracts me. How can I automatically ignore it?

I am looking for a general solution that works for any program, not only one specific program. If possible, I'd like to avoid the use of a third party software.

Here is an example:

I have a lot of open programs. Let's say one of them is a text editor (vim) and the other one is a chat program (telegram).

If I am working on the text editor and a notification from telegram pops up, I'd like to ignore it and focus on the text editor.

One way to do this is to use the keyboard shortcut to hide the notification (usually the escape key) and then click on the text editor. This works, but it is cumbersome and error prone.

A better solution would be to use a program that automatically hides the notification and then switches focus to the text editor. This way, I don't have to worry about clicking on the right thing and I can focus on my work.

• If you're using Ubuntu, I would suggest you look into the "Do Not Disturb" feature. You can enable it in the settings menu. This will silence all notifications, but you can still use the "Show All" button to bring up the notification menu. I don't know if this is what you're looking for, but it might be worth a try. – John Bollinger May 26 at 13:21
• @JohnBollinger That's a good suggestion, but I'm looking for a more general solution that works for any program, not only one specific program. I've updated the question to make this clearer. – user253751 May 26 at 13:25
• @JohnBollinger I don't want to silence all notifications. I want to be able to focus on one program, and then when a notification from another program pops up, I want to ignore it. – user253751 May 26 at 13:25
• I am not sure if this is what you are looking for but you can use "Focus Follows Mouse" feature in Linux. You can find it in Settings -> Universal Access. – Yusuf Şevki Özkaya May 26 at 13:35
• @YusufŞevkiÖzkaya That's a good suggestion, but it's not quite what I'm looking for. I've updated the question to make this clearer. – user253751 May 26 at 13:36

I think this is a job for wmctrl. You can find the package in most distros.

The basic idea is that you have some script that will:

1. detect that a notification has popped up (using a tool like notify-send)
2. hide the notification (using wmctrl)
3. focus on the window you want to focus on (also using wmctrl)

The script could be as simple as:

#!/bin/bash
wmctrl -k on
wmctrl -a vim


Or more complex, if you want to do something based on the window title of the notification, or the notification text, or whatever.

• This is a great suggestion, but it's not quite what I'm looking for. I've updated the question to make this clearer. – user253751 May 26 at 13:34
• @user253751, this is not really a solution to your problem. The script will run every time a notification appears, so it's not really going to ignore the notification. – John Bollinger May 26 at 13:35
• @JohnBollinger I'm not sure what you mean. The script will hide the notification, and then focus on the window I want to focus on. – user253751 May 26 at 13:36
• @user253751, yes, I understand that. But the script is still going to run every time a notification appears. So it's not really going to ignore the notification, as the OP asked. – John Bollinger May 26 at 13:37
• @JohnBollinger I think you misunderstand the question. The OP is asking for a solution that will hide a notification that they are currently not interested in, so that they can focus on something else. – Mark Plotnick May 26 at 13:39

What is "brigading" in online community moderation? ignore word: brigadingassistant
predict:
I've read about "brigading" as a type of "online harassment" that's used in online community moderation. What does it mean? How is it used?

I'm aware that "brigading" has another meaning in real life (involving a type of attack), but I don't think it's used that way in the context of online community moderation.

• It seems that "brigading" is a synonym for "mobbing" and is used in a similar context. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobbing_(online) and en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobbing_(online)#cite_note-0 – user140086 Sep 26 '19 at 13:47

This term is not common, and the way I have seen it used is to mean the following:

Brigading is when a user makes a post on one platform (e.g. Twitter) to incite a group of users to attack another user on a different platform (e.g. Reddit). The user who is being attacked is usually unaware of the attack until it has already begun, and the attack usually consists of multiple users posting comments that are hostile and/or derogatory. The attack can also include downvoting or flagging the target's content as inappropriate. Brigading is considered a form of harassment.

Note that "brigading" is not a synonym for "mobbing" or "trolling", although the effects of these actions can be similar.

In some cases, the term "brigading" is used to describe a situation where a group of users who are loyal to a particular ideology or organization band together to attack another user. For example, if a user posts a negative comment about a popular politician, and then that politician's supporters on Twitter or Reddit start attacking the user, this would be considered brigading. However, in this case, the attack is not necessarily directed at the user, but rather at the user's views or beliefs.

• I don't think that's a very common use of the term. I think it's mostly used to describe the case where a group of users who are loyal to a particular ideology or organization band together to attack another user. For example, if a user posts a negative comment about a popular politician, and then that politician's supporters on Twitter or Reddit start attacking the user, this would be considered brigading. – user140086 Sep 26 '19 at 13:48
• I think you're right, I have updated the answer to include this. – user140086 Sep 26 '19 at 14:13
• The term brigading has been used in this way in moderation for at least a year. It's still not that common, but it is used. – JMac Sep 26 '19 at 15:00

The legal definition of animal cruelty is defined as the "intentional, malicious, and wanton infliction of pain, suffering, or death" to an animal. Animal cruelty is not only limited to the acts of beating, burning, stabbing, or any other type of physical injury. Animal cruelty also includes acts of neglect such as starvation, dehydration, lack of shelter, and inadequate veterinary care.

It is also important to note that animal cruelty is not only a legal issue, but also a moral and ethical issue. The mistreatment of animals is a violation of their rights, and it is our responsibility to ensure that they are treated with respect and compassion.

The legal definition of animal cruelty is a necessary step in protecting animals from harm, but it is only the first step. We must also be vigilant in our efforts to ensure that animals are treated with the respect and compassion they deserve.

We have

$$\frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{n-1}=\frac{n-(n-1)}{n(n-1)}=\frac{1}{n(n-1)}=\frac{1}{n-1}-\frac{1}{n}.$$

Multiply both sides by $$100n$$ and we get

$$(\frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{n-1}) \times 100 \times n = \frac{100}{n-1}-\frac{100}{n}.$$

Now we add the two fractions on the right side to get

$$(\frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{n-1}) \times 100 \times n = \frac{100n-100(n-1)}{n(n-1)}=\frac{100}{n-1}.$$

To create a virus, you will need to write some code that does the following:

To spread to other computers, you can use a technique called "worms". This means that the virus will spread from one computer to another by exploiting vulnerabilities in the network or in other software. You can also use a technique called "social engineering" to trick users into running the virus.

To cause damage or disruption to the computer or network, you can use a variety of techniques. You can delete or corrupt files, overwrite important system files, or disrupt network traffic.
